Just how useful is it as a test? Suppose the &quot;good&quot; code is:<p><pre><code>  for (1..100) {
    my $fizz = ($_ % 3 == 0) ? &quot;Fizz&quot; : &quot;&quot;;
    my $buzz = ($_ % 5 == 0) ? &quot;Buzz&quot; : &quot;&quot;;
    ($fizz ne &quot;&quot; || $buzz ne &quot;&quot;) ? print &quot;$fizz$buzz
&quot;
            : print   &quot;$_
&quot;;
  }
</code></pre>
and the &quot;bad&quot; code is the one-liner:<p><pre><code>  print ( ((($_ % 3) ? &quot;&quot; : &quot;Fizz&quot;) . (($_ % 5) ? &quot;&quot; : &quot;Buzz&quot;))
     || $_, &quot;
&quot;) for (1..100);

</code></pre>
or is the following:<p><pre><code>  #!/usr/bin/perl
  @v=(0, &quot;Fizz&quot;, &quot;Buzz&quot;, &quot;FizzBuzz&quot;);
  for($v[0]=1;$v[0]<=100;$v[0]++){
	$k = ($v[0]%3)?0:1;
	$k += ($v[0]%5)?0:2;
	print($v[$k].&quot;
&quot;);
  }
</code></pre>
(All three from <a href="http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?FizzBuzzTest" rel="nofollow">http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?FizzBuzzTest</a> .)<p>What does that reveal about the interviewee that makes this a great interview topic? To my eye, I prefer #1, #3, and #2, but it starts to get into personal preference rather than anything seriously indicative.<p>Do you want to dock someone for not being able to give a seriously bad implementation?
